<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,540,1872,1899]" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">
Description. Imago (
<figureCitation box="[395,527,1872,1899]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–28" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1663,1688]" captionTargetBox="[237,1353,224,1596]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[227,1360,219,1599]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 19–28. 19. S. striata, male, Paterna del Madera, Albacete, (Spain) (coll. RMV); 20. S. striata, female, El Cerro, Gredilla la Polera, Burgos, (Spain) (coll. RMV); 21. S striata f. melanoptera, male, Loma del Rey, Quintanilla Sobresierra, Burgos, (Spain) (coll. RMV); 22. El Cerro, Gredilla la Polera, Burgos, (Spain) (coll. RMV); 23. S. slovenica, male, Crni Kal, Petrinje, (Slovenia) (coll. RMV); 24. S. slovenica, female, Crni Kal, Petrinje, (Slovenia) (coll. RMV); 25. S. Slovenica f. melanoptera, male, Goriski Kras, Kostanjevica, (Slovenia) (coll. RMV); 26. S. Slovenica f. melanoptera, female, Goriski Kras, Kostanjevica, (Slovenia) (coll. RMV); 27. L. bifasciata, male, Val d´Ese, Corse, (France) (coll. RMV); 28. L. bifasciata, female, Costa Smeralda, Sardinia, (Italy) (coll. RMV)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3246054/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="429">Figs 27–28</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Average wingspan 
<quantity box="[761,875,1872,1899]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.053" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" unit="mm" value="30.53">30.53 mm</quantity>
(n = 15; 
<quantity box="[979,1104,1872,1899]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="28" pageNumber="429" unit="mm" value="30.0" valueMax="35.0" valueMin="25.0">25–35 mm</quantity>
). Head and thorax large, eyes large, palps relatively long and proboscis functional, moderately long. Antenna of male medium-long bipectinate that of female filiform, thorax and abdomen covered with uniform scales. Foreleg tibia with a long and thin spur, forewings long, narrow, tip acute; hindwings broad, with a slightly concave outer margin. Females slightly larger and of a paler colour.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,152,755]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,481,152,179]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[383,468,152,179]" captionStart="FIGURE 39" captionStartId="27.[151,246,1726,1751]" captionTargetBox="[198,1374,878,1696]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[203,1385,895,1701]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 39. L. bifasciata, male and female genitalia, gen. prep. 5795JG m. Lecci, Corce, (France), 5794JG f. Lecci, Corce, (France)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3246068/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Uncus tubular with the form of a mace or spatula; valvae rectangular, elongated, with a pointed and rounded cucullus and a large upper process topped with a rounded tip that gives the valva the resemblance of a hump; saccus rounded, transtilla densely spiny. Aedeagus with pointed and rounded coecum, and at the other end a peculiar bulbous shape, filled with a considerable number of medium sized cornuti, highly sclerotized. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,355,296,323]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
Lamella antevaginalis highly sclerotized, broadly rectangular; ductus bursae membranous, short and wide; bursa medially constricted, but without spiral crown (as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1819" box="[927,1027,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Coscinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="430" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[927,1027,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">Coscinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); bursa with two visible signa.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,152,755]" box="[199,550,369,395]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,406,369,395]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">Immature stages.</emphasis>
Not studied.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,152,755]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,389,405,431]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">Molecular data.</emphasis>
The two genetically investigated specimens differ by 3.24% from each other. The two specimens were collected on different islands, one on 
<collectingCountry box="[732,818,441,467]" name="France" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">Corsica</collectingCountry>
(ZMBN Lep489) and the other on Sardinia (ZMBN Lep503). The closest uncorrected p-distance is 7.34% to a specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hübner" baseAuthorityYear="1804" box="[940,1134,477,503]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Coscinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="430" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysocephala">
<emphasis box="[940,1134,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">C. chrysocephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Sequencing of the nuclear wingless gene was not successful, most likely because of the age of the specimens (13–15 years).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,152,755]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rambur" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[151,364,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Lerautia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="430" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifasciata">
<emphasis box="[151,364,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">Lerautia bifasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is strongly supported (1.00 PP, 100% BS) and sister to an unsupported clade containing all other genetically investigated species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="430" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,152,755]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,620,647]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">Biology.</emphasis>
Bivoltine, flying from May to August. The two sexes are nocturnal and are attracted to artificial light. The species prefers karstic areas at intermediate to high altitudes. The larvae are polyphagous on a wide variety of plant species (
<bibRefCitation author="Witt, T. J. &amp; Ronkay, L." box="[309,550,693,719]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430" refId="ref27927" refString="Witt, T. J. &amp; Ronkay, L. (2011) Noctuidae Europaea. Lymantrinae and Arctiinae including Phylogeny and Check List of the Quadrifid Noctuoidea of Europe, 13. Entomological Press, Soro, 448 pp." type="book" year="2011">Witt &amp; Ronkay 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,999,728,755]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,152,755]" box="[199,999,728,755]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,459,728,755]" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">
Distribution (
<figureCitation box="[360,445,728,755]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1284,1309]" captionTargetBox="[235,1356,405,1234]" captionTargetId="figure@40.[227,1360,402,1238]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 61. Distribution map of L. bifasciata." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3246100/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">Fig. 61</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Endemic to the islands of 
<collectingCountry box="[758,844,729,755]" name="France" pageId="29" pageNumber="430">Corsica</collectingCountry>
and Sardinia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
